*Larry P. v. Riles* (1979) challenged the use of IQ tests that disproportionately placed Black students in special education, leading to a ruling that schools must ensure tests do not discriminate on the basis of race. The case established that standardized tests could not be used in a racially biased manner without valid evidence of fairness. This precedent reinforced the requirement for non-discriminatory educational assessments.
